I recently learnt that the expected number of prime factors for an integer $n$ is on the order of $\log\log n$ . This was apparently proven by Hardy and Ramanujan. This led to me wondering what the expected number of (total) factors for a given number is. I am aware that, if $n=p_1^{
u_1}p_2^{
u_2}p_3^{
u_3}\cdots p_k^{
u_k}$ , then the number of factors of $n$ is $\prod_{i=1}^k\left(
u_i+1ight)$ . I also know that $\displaystyle P(
u_i=a)= rac1{p_i^{~a}}$ .  Not sure how to proceed, though.

