This question already has answers here : How to prove: if $a,b \in \mathbb N$, then $a^{1/b}$ is an integer or an irrational number? (14 answers) Closed 6 years ago . Is my proof beneath perfect and complete? I wanted to prove that for any nth root of an integer, if it's not an integer, than it's irrational: $$ egin{cases} m,n\in \mathbb{N}\\sqrt[n]{m}
otin \mathbb{N} \end{cases}\implies \sqrt[n]{m}
otin \mathbb{Q}.$$ I start by assuming that $m^{ rac 1n}$ is rational and non-integer. So there exist  co-prime integers $a,b$ so that $$\sqrt[n]{m}= rac{a}{b}$$ $$\implies  m= rac{a^n}{b^n}\in\mathbb{N}.$$ But since $a$ and $b$ have no common factor, $a^n$ and $b^n$ also have no common factor. So: $$ rac{a^n}{b^n}
otin\mathbb{N},$$ a contradiction.

